                <td width=3D"100%" align=3D"LEFT" valign=3D"TOP"> <!-- Inst=
anceBeginEditable name=3D"MainTextArea" --><span class=3D"title">Tightening=
=20
                  the Nut or the Bolt?</span><br>
                  <hr noshade=3D"" width=3D"100%" color=3D"#FF0000">
                  <p><span class=3D"maintext"> The question is often asked =
as to=20
                    whether the nut or the bolt head should be tightened. T=
he=20
                    answer depends upon which tightening process is being u=
sed.=20
                    For torque controlled tightening whether the nut is tig=
htened=20
                    and the bolt head held, or the bolt head tightened and =
the=20
                    nut held, can be of importance.</span></p>
                  <p><span class=3D"maintext">The general objective from a =
tightening=20
                    process is to achieve a consistent bolt preload. Contro=
lling=20
                    the torque during tightening and completing subsequent =
inspection=20
                    checks to ensure that the specified torque is being ach=
ieved,=20
                    are common ways that this objective is implemented.</sp=
an></p>
                  <img src=3D"https://www.boltscience.com/images/torque-for=
ce-graph-800-549.gif" alt=3D"Torque-Force Graph" width=3D"800" vspace=3D"5"=
 hspace=3D"2" height=3D"549" align=3D"center">=20
                  &nbsp; <p></p> <span class=3D"maintext">=20
                  <p>When applied torque and the resulting tension (preload=
) in=20
                    the bolt are measured during tightening and plotted on =
a graph,=20
                    there is a linear relationship between the torque and t=
he=20
                    tension. The bolt tension is directly dependent, and pr=
oportional=20
                    to, the applied torque. This is illustrated by the grap=
h,=20
                    which is based upon experimental results, that is shown=
 in=20
                    the diagram above. From such test results it is possibl=
e to=20
                    establish the appropriate torque for a required bolt pr=
eload=20
                    that may be required.=20
                  </p><p>One of the disadvantages of using torque control i=
s that=20
                    there can be a significant variation in the bolt preloa=
d achieved=20
                    for a given torque value. There are several reasons for=
 this=20
                    e.g. inaccuracy in applying the torque, dimensional var=
iations=20
                    of the thread and hole size variation amoungst others. =
However,=20
                    the dominant factor is usually due to the frictional va=
riation=20
                    that is present between the contact surfaces that are b=
eing=20
                    rotated.=20
                  </p><p> <img src=3D"https://www.boltscience.com/images/pi=
echart.gif" alt=3D"Torque Distribution" width=3D"759" height=3D"531" align=
=3D"center"><br>
                  </p><p>From tests, it is known that approximately 50% of =
the tightening=20
                    torque is dissipated in overcoming friction under the b=
olt=20
                    head or the nut face (whichever is the face that is rot=
ated).=20
                    Typically only 10% to 15% of the overall torque is actu=
ally=20
                    used to tighten the bolt, the rest is used to overcome =
friction=20
                    in the threads and on the contact face that is being ro=
tated=20
                    (nut face or bolt head). This is illustrated in the pie=
chart=20
                    shown above. Relatively small changes in the nut face f=
riction=20
                    can have a significant effect on the bolt preload. As m=
ore=20
                    torque is perhaps needed to overcome friction, less rem=
ains=20
                    for the bolt extension and hence as the effect of adver=
sely=20
                    reducing the preload. If the friction under the nut fac=
e is=20
                    reduced, then, for a given torque, the bolt preload wil=
l be=20
                    increased.=20
                  </p><p><img src=3D"https://www.boltscience.com/images/joi=
nt1.gif" width=3D"415" height=3D"316" hspace=3D"5" align=3D"RIGHT">The=20
                    diagram shown at the side is perhaps the most common si=
tuation=20
                    where the top and bottom plates of the joint are made f=
rom=20
                    the same material, have the same finish and the hole si=
ze=20
                    is the same through both of the plates. For such a join=
t,=20
                    when the nut face and bolt head sizes have the same dia=
meter=20
                    and finish, it will not matter whether the bolt head or=
 the=20
                    nut is tightened. Some people believe that by tightenin=
g the=20
                    bolt head rather than the nut it will affect the torsio=
n in=20
                    bolt shank. The torsion in the shank of the bolt depend=
s upon=20
                    the thread friction torque. For a given finish conditio=
n,=20
                    the thread friction has some scatter associated with it=
, but=20
                    will not depend on whether the nut or the bolt head is =
tightened.=20
                    If the thread friction torque remains the same, the tor=
sion=20
                    in the shank will be the same irrespective of whether t=
he=20
                    bolt head or the nut is tightened.=20
                  </p><p><img src=3D"https://www.boltscience.com/images/joi=
nt2.gif" width=3D"415" height=3D"314" hspace=3D"5" align=3D"LEFT">=20
                    The diagram at the side shows the situation when the pl=
ates=20
                    comprising the joint are different materials (such as o=
ne=20
                    being steel and the other aluminium) or have different =
finishes=20
                    (such as one plate being galvanised and the other paint=
ed).=20
                    In such situations, it will, in general, be important a=
s to=20
                    whether the bolt head or nut is tightened. The reason i=
s that=20
                    each face will have a different friction coefficient. I=
f the=20
                    tightened torque was determined either by testing or by=
 looking=20
                    up the friction characteristics of the surface, say bas=
ed=20
                    upon the nut face, then it is probable that the head fa=
ce=20
                    would have a different friction coefficient. If it had =
a lower=20
                    friction value then the preload would be increased if t=
he=20
                    bolt head was tightened. In the extreme case, if the fr=
ictional=20
                    differences were large, bolt breakage could occur.=20
                  </p><p><img src=3D"https://www.boltscience.com/images/joi=
nt3.gif" width=3D"421" height=3D"327" hspace=3D"5" align=3D"RIGHT">=20
                    The diagram at the side illustrates the case when the c=
learance=20
                    hole in the top plate differs from that used in the bot=
tom=20
                    plate. Such situations are relatively common. There is =
an=20
                    effective friction radius on the part that is rotated (=
nut=20
                    or bolt head) that is usually taken as the mean of the =
clearance=20
                    hole and outer bearing face radii. Because this radii w=
ould=20
                    be greater for the bolt head than the nut in the situat=
ion=20
                    shown, less bolt preload would result by tightening the=
 bolt=20
                    head rather than the nut, other factors such as frictio=
n being=20
                    the same. Hence another example of a situation as to wh=
ether=20
                    the nut or bolt head is tightened.=20
                  </p><p><img src=3D"https://www.boltscience.com/images/joi=
nt4.gif" width=3D"414" height=3D"318" hspace=3D"5" align=3D"LEFT">=20
                    The drawing at the side the case when there are style a=
nd=20
                    dimensional differences between the bolt head and the n=
ut.=20
                    The effect is similar to that which happens in the prev=
ious=20
                    case. Differences in the friction radii between the bol=
t head=20
                    and the nut-washer interface result in the preload bein=
g affected=20
                    by which item is tightened. In the case shown here, the=
re=20
                    would probably also be differences between the friction=
 coefficient=20
                    that is present when the nut is tightened on the washer=
 and=20
                    the bolt head onto the joint. This would increase the v=
ariability=20
                    still further.=20
                  </p><p>Washers are occasionally used as a means of minimi=
sing frictional=20
                    scatter besides the common reason of reducing the beari=
ng=20
                    stress on the joint face. The friction condition betwee=
n the=20
                    washer and nut face can be reasonably well defined and =
controlled,=20
                    more so than the joint surfaces usually can. By control=
ling=20
                    the friction, the preload can be more reliably achieved=
. To=20
                    do this consistently, a close fit is needed on the insi=
de=20
                    diameter of the washer. One way in which this can be ac=
hieved=20
                    is by the use of a SEMS unit (in which a washer is held=
 captive=20
                    on the bolt shank). The same can be achieved by using a=
 KEPS=20
                    unit (a washer being held captive on a nut).
                  </p><p>So in general, when using torque control, tighteni=
ng the=20
                    bolt by rotating the bolt head or the nut can matter. I=
t is=20
                    good practice to specify which part should be tightened=
 so=20
                    that the bolt preload variation is minimised.<br>
				=09
                    <span class=3D"maintext">There is an article on this to=
pic that you may also find of interest.</span></p>
                  </span><span class=3D"maintext">
				    <table width=3D"775" border=3D"1" cellspacing=3D"1" cellpadding=3D"=
5">=20
				  <tbody><tr>=20
                      <td width=3D"584"><p><span class=3D"newstitle">What s=
hould be=20
                          tightened the nut or the bolt head?</span></p>
                        <p><span class=3D"maintext">Published in March 2006=
 issue=20
                          of Fastener and Fixing Europe, this article discu=
sses=20
                          the question of whether the nut or bolt head shou=
ld=20
                          be tightened and whether it makes any difference?=
 The=20
                          answer depends upon which tightening process is b=
eing=20
                          used. For torque controlled tightening whether th=
e nut=20
                          is tightened and the bolt head held, or the bolt =
head=20
                          tightened and the nut held, can be of importance.=
</span></p>
                        <p><span class=3D"maintext">The general objective f=
rom a=20
                          tightening process is to achieve a consistent bol=
t preload.=20
                          Controlling the torque during tightening and comp=
leting=20
                          subsequent inspection checks to ensure that the s=
pecified=20
                          torque is being achieved, are common ways that th=
is=20
                          objective is implemented.</span></p>
                        <p><span class=3D"maintext">This article shows that=
, in=20
                          general, when using torque control, tightening th=
e bolt=20
                          by rotating the bolt head or the nut can matter. =
It=20
                          is good practice to specify which part should be =
tightened=20
                          so that the bolt preload variation is minimised. =
The=20
                          issues involved are discussed.</span></p>
                        </td>
                      <td width=3D"178"><a href=3D"https://www.boltscience.=
com/pages/what-should-be-tightened-the-nut-or-the-bolt-head.pdf" title=3D"W=
hat should be tightened - the nut or the bolt head"><img src=3D"https://www=
.boltscience.com/images/What%20should%20be%20tightened%20-%20the%20nut%20or=
%20the%20bolt%20head.png" width=3D"174" height=3D"250"></a></td>
                    </tr></tbody></table>
				 =20
                  <p>To assist the Engineer in overcoming the problems asso=
ciated=20
                    with the use of threaded fasteners and bolted joints, B=
olt=20
                    Science has developed a number of computer <b><a href=
=3D"https://www.boltscience.com/pages/software.htm">programs</a></b>.=20
                    These programs are designed to be easy to use so that a=
n engineer=20
                    without detailed knowledge in this field can solve prob=
lems=20
                    related to this subject.</p>
                  </span>=20
